    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>A Clean Vote in Mexico</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Sandra Fuentes-Berain says, contrary to June 28 editorial, there is no chance that electoral chicanery will decide winner in Mexico's presidential election; claims electoral reform in Mexico has built one of most fraud-free voting systems in world</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Clean Vote Vowed in Mexico, but Fraud Dies Hard'' (news article, June 28):</p>
        <p>You fail to make the case that electoral chicanery could decide the winner in Mexico's presidential election on Sunday.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Clean Vote Vowed in Mexico, but Fraud Dies Hard'' (news article, June 28):</p>
        <p>You fail to make the case that electoral chicanery could decide the winner in Mexico's presidential election on Sunday.</p>
        <p>Electoral reforms in Mexico have built one of the most fraud-free voting systems in the world. Balloting is overseen by an independent elections commission in 113,000 polling stations, monitored by 450,000 representatives from the different political parties and 860 foreign observers, including former President Jimmy Carter.</p>
        <p>Election violations will be punished by the commission or the attorney general with sanctions ranging from immediate arrest to stiff fines to cancellation of the responsible political party's charter.</p>
        <p>SANDRA FUENTES-BERAIN  Coordinator, Intl. Affairs  Institutional Revolutionary Party  Mexico City, June 30, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
